00:23:00.780 --> 00:23:03.590
So it would be great
if we could uncover

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:07.220
the fundamental causal variance
for prediction analysis

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:10.070
because that would take away
a lot of this correlation

00:23:10.070 --> 00:23:11.547
not causation issue.

00:23:11.547 --> 00:23:13.130
Unfortunately,
Mendelian randomization

00:23:13.130 --> 00:23:14.963
also requires that you
have a really, really

00:23:14.963 --> 00:23:17.120
strong, precise
instrument for uncovering

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:18.560
those causal relationships.

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:20.840
And the vast majority of
our genetic instrument

00:23:20.840 --> 00:23:24.350
are relatively weak effects that
we're not really confident in.

00:23:24.350 --> 00:23:26.840
So Mendelian
randomization is going

00:23:26.840 --> 00:23:28.970
to be a really important
tool for understanding

00:23:28.970 --> 00:23:31.490
the causal relationships
between pairs of traits

00:23:31.490 --> 00:23:35.175
but not necessarily for
building more useful predictors.

00:23:35.175 --> 00:23:36.050
Does that make sense?

00:23:38.990 --> 00:23:40.650
- I have a question, Alicia.

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:43.790
So I can share in the
enthusiasm to want

00:23:43.790 --> 00:23:48.290
to bring these prediction
kits to the market.

00:23:48.290 --> 00:23:51.860
But are we getting a little
ahead of ourselves in terms of

00:23:51.860 --> 00:23:55.580
are we outpacing the clinic?

00:23:55.580 --> 00:23:57.080
We want to bring
them to the clinic.

00:23:57.080 --> 00:23:58.910
But we're outpacing.

00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:05.810
How will they impact
clinical management?

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:08.960
I mean, clearly we're outpacing
the treatment options.

00:24:08.960 --> 00:24:11.030
So I wanted to know if you can--

00:24:11.030 --> 00:24:12.920
- Yeah, absolutely--
that's a great question.

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:14.370
And it's a really great point.

00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:17.150
So I think genetics
in general is not

00:24:17.150 --> 00:24:20.930
super useful for clinical
translation today.

00:24:20.930 --> 00:24:23.239
But I wouldn't necessarily
bet against human genetics

00:24:23.239 --> 00:24:24.780
over the course of
the coming decade.

00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:27.154
So I think it's important to
start thinking about it now.

00:24:27.154 --> 00:24:29.870
Because we've seen over the
course of the past decade

00:24:29.870 --> 00:24:32.930
that our studies have gone from
being hundreds of individuals

00:24:32.930 --> 00:24:35.960
at a time being studied to now
even millions of individuals

00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:37.054
being studied at a time.

00:24:37.054 --> 00:24:38.720
So I think it's sort
of a matter of time

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:40.340
before this is
clinically translated.

00:24:40.340 --> 00:24:42.380
And I think to head off
some of these issues,

00:24:42.380 --> 00:24:43.860
we really need to
think about them

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:47.060
now if we're trying to make
sure that we have equitable

00:24:47.060 --> 00:24:50.390
translation and don't exacerbate
existing health disparities.

00:24:50.390 --> 00:24:51.080
- OK.

00:24:51.080 --> 00:24:51.600
Yes?

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:52.100
- Thanks.

00:24:52.100 --> 00:24:56.000
Quick question-- these GWAS
studies have been around

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:56.990
for a few years.

00:24:56.990 --> 00:25:00.590
And the earlier studies
were shorter read length

00:25:00.590 --> 00:25:01.790
and much more expensive.

00:25:01.790 --> 00:25:04.952
The first one cost $3 billion.

00:25:04.952 --> 00:25:07.350
So obviously, the
disparities issue--

00:25:07.350 --> 00:25:11.110
have you ever tried to quantify
what it would cost to catch up?

00:25:11.110 --> 00:25:13.190
So the tests are much,
much cheaper now.

00:25:13.190 --> 00:25:15.050
And you can do a
whole genome scan

00:25:15.050 --> 00:25:18.230
for what it costs you a lot
more to do even a partial exome.

00:25:18.230 --> 00:25:23.057
So if you put a number on it,
maybe somebody would donate.

00:25:23.057 --> 00:25:24.390
- That's a really good question.

00:25:24.390 --> 00:25:25.235
And it's a really good point.

00:25:25.235 --> 00:25:26.860
One thing that we're
trying to think of

00:25:26.860 --> 00:25:30.109
is what the costs of
these health disparities

00:25:30.109 --> 00:25:31.400
would potentially translate to.

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:32.775
But I think your
question is more

00:25:32.775 --> 00:25:35.840
about what would it take
to even these burdens

00:25:35.840 --> 00:25:38.060
and generally do these
studies at as large a scale

00:25:38.060 --> 00:25:39.932
and many different phenotypes?

00:25:39.932 --> 00:25:42.140
So I it depends on which
phenotype you're looking at.

00:25:42.140 --> 00:25:43.806
Like if you're looking
at schizophrenia,

00:25:43.806 --> 00:25:46.730
let's say, the largest
European cohorts currently

00:25:46.730 --> 00:25:50.150
have 150,000
participants, about half

00:25:50.150 --> 00:25:52.700
of those of which are cases
and half of which are controls.

00:25:52.700 --> 00:25:57.030
So 150,000 individuals at about
$50 a genotyping array plus

00:25:57.030 --> 00:26:00.920
some analytical costs, it's
a hugely expensive problem.

00:26:00.920 --> 00:26:03.440
But I think we need to start
pushing the needle forward

00:26:03.440 --> 00:26:05.780
to be including these.

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:07.640
- And the very last question.

00:26:07.640 --> 00:26:09.290
- I love genetics.

00:26:09.290 --> 00:26:11.510
But your first slide
started out with

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:16.220
environmental contributions
and genetic contributions.

00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:19.290
So how are you going to deal
with the fact that some things,

00:26:19.290 --> 00:26:20.600
it doesn't matter what you do?

00:26:20.600 --> 00:26:22.520
Your genes are your genes.

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:24.920
But other things,
you know, you haven't

00:26:24.920 --> 00:26:27.680
accounted for the
environmental aspects,

00:26:27.680 --> 00:26:31.230
especially in things that are
going into precision medicine.

00:26:31.230 --> 00:26:31.730
- Yeah.

00:26:31.730 --> 00:26:32.938
That's a great point as well.

00:26:32.938 --> 00:26:34.760
So I wanted to make
sure that the point was

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.870
very clear that genetics
is not deterministic.

00:26:36.870 --> 00:26:40.075
So especially for a lot of
these much more complex traits,

00:26:40.075 --> 00:26:41.450
there is always
something you can

00:26:41.450 --> 00:26:43.460
do to tweak your
environment to reduce

00:26:43.460 --> 00:26:46.640
your risk of overall disease.

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:48.391
For the traits that
are not super genetic,

00:26:48.391 --> 00:26:50.223
I don't think genetic
risk scores are really

00:26:50.223 --> 00:26:52.610
going to add that much value
to a clinical translational.

00:26:52.610 --> 00:26:55.280
It's more the traits that
do have a pretty significant

00:26:55.280 --> 00:26:57.113
heritable component
that we're going to make

00:26:57.113 --> 00:27:00.790
the most inroads clinically.

00:27:00.790 --> 00:27:01.510
